{{Munabao|collapse=y}}

'''Munabao railway station''' is located in [[Barmer district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of  [[Rajasthan]].  It is a railway transit point on the India-Pakistan border.

==The railway station==
Munabao railway station is at an elevation of {{convert|80|m|ft}} and was assigned the code – MBF.<ref name=munabao>{{cite web|url= http://indiarailinfo.com/arrivals/munabao-mbf/2269|title= Arrivals at Munabao|publisher= indiarailinfo| accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>

==History==
A {{RailGauge|1000mm}} wide [[metre gauge]] line from Luni to Shadipalli, in Sind, was built across the [[Thar desert]] in 1902 and the line from Shadipalli to Hyderabad (now in Pakistan) was regauged.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-history3.html|title = IR History: Part III (1900-1947)| publisher=IRFCA | accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref>
The Luni-Barmer-Munabao section was converted to {{RailGauge|1676mm}} wide [[Indian gauge|broad gauge]] in 2004.<ref name=geography>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/faq/faq-inter.html |title = Geography:International| publisher=IRFCA | accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref>

According to a 1929 issue of the Railway Gazette, the [[Sind Mail]] used to run on this route between [[Ahmedabad]] and [[Hyderabad, Sindh]]. The route was in use with through services between [[Jodhpur]] and [[Karachi]] till around 1965. On the Pakistan side, [[Khokhrapar]] was the terminus of a metre gauge branch line from [[Hyderabad, Sindh]] via [[Mirpur Khas]], 135&nbsp;km from the border.<ref name=geography/>

The rail link across Munabao-Khokhrapar border was restored in 2006. As per the agreement between [[India]]n and [[Pakistan]] railways, the [[Thar Express]] travels once a week from Karachi during a six-month block, crosses the international border, and the passengers change over to an Indian train at [[Munabao]] for their onward journey to [[Bhagat Ki Kothi]] in [[Jodhpur]].<ref>{{cite web| url =http://www.thehindu.com/news/international/article931198.ece |title = Thar Express survives 'terror attack'| first= Mohammed|last= Iqbal| publisher=The Hindu, 5 December 2010 | accessdate = 30 April 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://nation.com.pk/national/17-Nov-2014/india-limits-thar-express-passengers-to-700  India limits Thar Express passengers to 700 ]</ref>

On the Indian side the [[Thar Express|Thar Link Express]] runs non-stop once a week from [[Bhagat Ki Kothi railway station|Bhagat Ki Kothi]] (near [[Jodhpur]]) to [[Munabao]] and back.<ref name=munabao/> [[Pakistan Railways]] have set up a new railway station at [[Zero Point railway station|Zero Point]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://208.112.102.150/PrintEdition.aspx?ID=4700&Cat=13&dt=12/11/2006| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140313154151/http://208.112.102.150/PrintEdition.aspx?ID=4700&Cat=13&dt=12%2F11%2F2006| dead-url=yes| archive-date=13 March 2014| title=Khokhrapar station to be operational soon| publisher=The News| date=12 December 2006| accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> There is a passenger train linking [[Munabao]] to [[Barmer, Rajasthan|Barmer]], which runs on all days except Monday.<ref name=munabao/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.bhaskar.com/news-fbo/c-10-2389570-jp0925-NOR.html |title=Bhaskar News |access-date=25 March 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160311154743/http://www.bhaskar.com/news-fbo/c-10-2389570-jp0925-NOR.html |archive-date=11 March 2016 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>

